Let `α` be a `CompleteLattice` and let `T` be a subset of `α`. The relative `Topology.lower` on `T`
takes on a particularly simple form when every element of `T` is `InfPrime` in `α`. In this case,
the relative-open sets are exactly the sets of the form `T ↓∩ (Ici a)ᶜ` for some `a` in `α`.

The pair of maps `S → ⊓ S` and `a → T ↓∩ Ici a` are often referred to as the kernel and the hull.
They form an antitone Galois connection between the subsets of `T` and `α`. When `α` can be generated
from `T` by taking infs, this becomes a Galois insertion and the topological closure coincides with
the closure arising from the Galois insertion. For this reason the relative lower topology on `T` is
often referred to as the hull-kernel topology. The names Jacobson topology and structure topology
also occur in the literature.

---

Actually, we need both `CompleteSublatticeSup` and `CompleteSublatticeInf` (being closed under suprema doesn't imply being closed under infima), then we can define `CompleteSublatticeSup.closure` and `CompleteSublatticeInf.closure`.
This is suspicious... I suspect I need to read the references to understand, but I won't have time before another week.

I probably got the idea for this approach from Henriksen et al https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s000120050056. The hull kernel topology on the Primitive Spectrum of a C*-algebra is discussed in most introductory texts on C*-algebras. Various related concepts are used in more specialist applications.

However, one can get a long way with both the basic results and the specialist applications without reference to C*-algebras. Much of the theory depends just on the Primitive Spectrum being a dense order-generating subset of the prime elements of the lattice of norm-closed two-sided ideals of the C*-algebra. The advantage of taking this point of view is that the results then apply in more general situations like the lattice norm-closed ideals of a JB*-algebra or even the lattice of M-ideals of a Banach space. Henriksen et al also make a connection to minimal primes in algebraic lattices.

AFAIK we don't have two sided ideals in Mathlib yet, so I couldn't develop this theory specifically for C*-algebras even if I wanted to.

I don't know if there's an accepted term for a dense, order-generating subset of the prime elements of a lattice. I ended up calling such sets "primitive" in my doctoral thesis, but I was never very satisfied with that as a name.

> I probably got the idea for this approach from Henriksen et al https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s000120050056. The hull kernel topology on the Primitive Spectrum of a C*-algebra is discussed in most introductory texts on C*-algebras. Various related concepts are used in more specialist applications.

> However, one can get a long way with both the basic results and the specialist applications without reference to C*-algebras. Much of the theory depends just on the Primitive Spectrum being a dense order-generating subset of the prime elements of the lattice of norm-closed two-sided ideals of the C*-algebra.

Maybe @j-loreaux will have an opinion on how your general machinery should interface with C*-algebras. What `T` will you take then? Shouldn't `ht : ∀ p ∈ T, InfPrime p` be automatically provided by typeclass inference then (by making that predicate a typeclass)?

> AFAIK we don't have two sided ideals in Mathlib yet, so I couldn't develop this theory specifically for C*-algebras even if I wanted to.

#13401 and #13902 are relevant.

Let `A` be a Banach space and let `δₑA^*₁` be the set of extreme points of the dual unit ball. For each `x` in `δₑA^*₁` let `kₙ(ker x)` be the largest M-ideal of `A` contained in the kernel `ker x` of `x`. Then α would be the lattice of M-ideals in `A` and `T` would be `Prim A`, the set of M-ideals `{ kₙ(ker x) : x ∈ δₑA^*₁ }`.

So `ht` here is a fact that you establish once and for all, right? I think it should therefore be a typeclass.

Or maybe what you want is replacing `T` by `f : ι → {p // InfPrime p}`?
